"script": "On Earth, sunsets blaze red and orange. But stand on Mars, and the sunset turns an eerie, icy blue. You see, Mars is coated in fine red dust floating in its thin air. During the day, that dust scatters the warm colors and tints the whole sky a dull butterscotch. But as the Sun sinks low, the dust filters out the red light and lets the blue slip through, pooling right around the setting Sun. So on a planet that looks blood-red all day, the only blue you'll ever see arrives at nightfall.",
